## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2020 Vermont Medical Center ransomware attack** — a significant incident that took the hospital's network offline for weeks and directly affected patient care across the facility. Staff could not access electronic records, laboratory systems, and pharmacy systems. Cancer patients had appointments delayed. The recovery took months and cost an estimated $63 million.

What made this case particularly relevant to today's topic is the availability dimension. Vermont Medical Center is a full-service hospital where the EHR system is deeply integrated into clinical workflows across every department. The availability impact of losing that system was not just inconvenient — it was operationally catastrophic in ways that directly affected patients.

A FIPS 199 categorization exercise for Vermont Medical Center's EHR would have produced a High availability rating — which would have required contingency planning controls at the High baseline level, including tested backup and recovery procedures, offline access capabilities, and documented downtime procedures for all clinical workflows that depend on the system.

Whether those controls were in place before the attack is not fully public. But the scale of the operational impact — weeks of disruption, $63 million in recovery costs, direct effects on patient care — illustrates exactly what High availability impact means in practice for a healthcare EHR. It is not an abstract categorization. It is a prediction of consequences that the security program needs to be designed to prevent or recover from.

